title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson DA .38 2nd model exc condition
postcontent: Here is a Smith and Wesson Double action .38from approximately 1883. The original nickel finish comes in at about 50% with a nice even patina. The pictures look like rust but there is no rust on this pistol. According to the serial number it is a .38 double action 2nd model. These were made between 1880 and 1884 with 115000 manufactured it has a 5 digit SN which puts it around 1882 or 3. It sports what I believe is probably original S&W walnut target stocks, they are a sound tight fit and obviously have been on the gun for a long time. The gun however does not have the adjustable sights which are very rare and didn’t come out until the third model. However the grips were available for the 2nd model. It is a very comfortable balanced revolver. The bore is immaculate as are the chambers with no corrosion or pitting present(how often do you see that!) The timing and lock up are right and tight and rock solid. The recoil plate shows very little signs of use as  does the front of the cylinder. I don’t believe this revolver has been shot much if at all in it’s 130 years of life. The mechanics on this little guy are better than many modern revolvers.

FYI: "629-1 was original and came about in 1982 or so, based on the blued model 29. starting with the 629-2E and 629-3 models in the late 80s, there was a beefed-up cylinder hand/star/and locking bolt. title: For Sale:  2 NIB Vepr 12 Russian AK style shotguns RPK strength not Saiga 12 unfired
location: S/W Denver Metro Area, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
$1450 obo/ea. - I have 2 identical New In Box, unfired, Vepr 12 Russian 12 ga. shotguns.  These are built as seen in Russia by the famed Molot factory, which uses heavy RPK strength receivers, unlike their inferior Izmash built cousins, the Saiga 12.  These shotguns come from the factory in the original AK pistol grip configuration.  Saiga 12s are imported with the trigger group moved back and have to be "converted" in the US, and are often converted by do-it-youselfers at home.  Even some of the "professional" conversions are crappy and have reliability issues.  The Vepr 12s are famous for shooting all types of shells without any modifications, thanks to their improved gas system.  The Vepr 12s also have a magwell and the magazine inserts like an AR mag, instead of having to be rocked in like a standard AK.  This makes for much faster and easier mag changes.  However, this also means standard Saiga 12 mags do not work in a Vepr.  You must use a mag made for the Vepr 12.  These come with the original box, manual and one factory 5 rd mag.  I have a couple extra 12 round Vepr stick mags for $75 ea (as seen in one of the pics).  The last pic shows the difference between a converted Saiga 12 (top) and a factory built Vepr 12.

Get yours while you can.  On July 1, you can no longer get the hi-cap mags or do a private transfer.  You will have to go through the de-facto Chickenlooper/Dumbocrat registration scheme.

Cash only - Face to Face transfer in the S/W Metro Denver area.  Must be 18+ with a valid CO driver's license and/or CCW.  No felons, gangsters, or otherwise prohibited persons.

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1911 GI vs milspec
postcontent:
Don't be duped into buying something falsely advertised. Someone here is claiming his GI model is "Milspec". Milspec obviously commands a higher price.  Always do your research. For example, new Milspec models sell in $600-$700 price range. New GI models sell for $450-$500 price range. Huge difference in specs and in price. Dad's in Gulfport has a new Milspec for $620. The following link has a good explanation of the difference.

http://www.1911talk.com/forum/springfield-armory/228-usgi-vs-mil-spec.html

Note, the obvious differences in the two in the provided photos. The first picture is of the GI model, with the vertical slide serrations and "U.S" on the grip panel, but not seen in it is the lanyard loop at the bottom of the grip. The second picture is the Milspec model.   Don't be a sucker!

It's a Model 1917 (an updated 1907 with the fat grip) that lacks the model designation stamp on the side, added later in the production. Serial number is in the 240xxx range (an online lookup I found through google estimates a production date of 1920). 

Aside from normal use marks, the finish is worn in places. The worst you can see on the sides of the frame below the cocking serrations & near the muzzle. A lot of bluing remains elsewhere & the gun has been spared by the rust monster. Trigger still shows case-hardening. Armslist limits me to 3 pics but I can take plenty if you want. I field stripped & fired the pistol and everything seems fine EXCEPT the magazine.. I don't know if it's the factory original or bad aftermarket parts, but it does not seat well and it does not feed rounds, they just go nose up. The mag follower doesn't move smoothly, seems to be riding on a rusty bent spring. Replacement aftermarket mags are available from Triple K if one was inclined to get this old gun checked out & turn it into a plinker again.
